File: Bloomberg quotes sources as saying the World Bank has also requested that any money loaned can't be used to bail out state-owned companies. Wikimedia Commons JOHANNESBURG - Treasury is yet to respond to reports that the World Bank has asked it to cut the government wage bill as a condition for receiving a $2-billion loan. Bloomberg quotes sources as saying the World Bank has also requested that any money loaned can't be used to bail out state-owned companies. READ: World Bank cuts SA's growth forecast South Africa has approached multilateral lenders for the first time since the end of apartheid as it tries to kickstart an economy battered by COVID-19. So far, the country has borrowed $1-billion from the New Development Bank, $4.3-billion from the International Monetary Fund, R5-billion from the African Development Bank and $50-million from the World Bank.